important to say,

00:11:58.350 --> 00:12:02.020
maybe, is that we've come
to a point in society

00:12:02.020 --> 00:12:05.620
where we're faced with some
huge social and environmental

00:12:05.620 --> 00:12:09.890
challenges, and a lot
of those challenges

00:12:09.890 --> 00:12:13.340
can't be solved simply through
kind of traditional means

00:12:13.340 --> 00:12:15.617
like nonprofits and government.

00:12:15.617 --> 00:12:17.450
It's not that those
aren't really important,

00:12:17.450 --> 00:12:19.880
they're necessary, but they're
insufficient to solving

00:12:19.880 --> 00:12:20.810
some of our biggest challenges.

00:12:20.810 --> 00:12:22.610
And the reason for
that is that they're

00:12:22.610 --> 00:12:24.350
inherently limited
in their ability

00:12:24.350 --> 00:12:28.670
to scale, to attract
capital, to attract talent.

00:12:28.670 --> 00:12:32.720
And business makes
up 75% or 80% of GDP.

00:12:32.720 --> 00:12:35.650
So either business is going
to be part of the problem,

00:12:35.650 --> 00:12:38.950
or it's going to be
part of the solution.

00:12:38.950 --> 00:12:44.310
And what we've seen is this
incredible-- particularly

00:12:44.310 --> 00:12:46.760
amongst younger people--
but this incredible

00:12:46.760 --> 00:12:49.870
outpouring of entrepreneurship,
of people wanting

00:12:49.870 --> 00:12:53.210
to use business
to create change.

00:12:53.210 --> 00:12:56.850
And so our feeling
has been, there

00:12:56.850 --> 00:12:59.549
are some impediments
to that, most of which

00:12:59.549 --> 00:13:00.840
are just kind of like cultural.

00:13:00.840 --> 00:13:02.923
People just aren't used
to thinking about business

00:13:02.923 --> 00:13:05.874
as a tool for positive
social change.

00:13:05.874 --> 00:13:07.790
And that means that
there's not all the market

00:13:07.790 --> 00:13:09.224
infrastructure built up.

00:13:09.224 --> 00:13:10.390
There's not the information.

00:13:10.390 --> 00:13:11.931
There's no way to
tell the difference

00:13:11.931 --> 00:13:14.240
between a good company
and just good marketing.

00:13:14.240 --> 00:13:18.120
And companies know-- you guys
know this-- companies know

00:13:18.120 --> 00:13:20.340
that consumers care
and the people who

00:13:20.340 --> 00:13:22.030
come to work at
their companies care

00:13:22.030 --> 00:13:25.310
a ton about how
companies behave.

00:13:25.310 --> 00:13:26.950
And so more and more
companies market

00:13:26.950 --> 00:13:31.750
themselves as being green
or responsible or social

00:13:31.750 --> 00:13:33.629
or whatever it is.

00:13:33.629 --> 00:13:35.170
And it's hard to
tell the difference.

00:13:35.170 --> 00:13:39.630
And so our instinct
originally was,

00:13:39.630 --> 00:13:41.837
we need some
organizing principles

00:13:41.837 --> 00:13:43.420
so that everybody
knows the difference

00:13:43.420 --> 00:13:45.370
between a good company
and good marketing,

00:13:45.370 --> 00:13:47.720
can identify those companies,
and then support them,

00:13:47.720 --> 00:13:49.540
whether it's going
to work at them,

00:13:49.540 --> 00:13:52.930
or starting them,
or buying from them.

00:13:52.930 --> 00:13:55.300
And there's huge power
in all of those companies

00:13:55.300 --> 00:13:57.930
then being able to get
together and speak collectively

00:13:57.930 --> 00:13:58.760
with one voice.

00:13:58.760 --> 00:14:01.970
HOST: That's a good point,
and I think specifically

00:14:01.970 --> 00:14:04.060
the point around
it being so easy

00:14:04.060 --> 00:14:06.480
to market yourself as being
a responsible company.

00:14:06.480 --> 00:14:11.690
We've seen a huge surge in just
marketing around sustainability

00:14:11.690 --> 00:14:14.760
and responsibility and
renewal, and we're giving back

00:14:14.760 --> 00:14:18.050
to the community, and
part of our profits.

00:14:18.050 --> 00:14:21.430
In starting Greyston, Mike,
why was it important for you

00:14:21.430 --> 00:14:24.489
to make sure that you
were a B Corp versus any

00:14:24.489 --> 00:14:26.530
of the other social programs
you could have done,

00:14:26.530 --> 00:14:27.988
or even marketing
efforts you could

00:14:27.988 --> 00:14:31.352
have done to be good
for the community?

00:14:31.352 --> 00:14:32.460
MIKE BRADY: Yeah.

00:14:32.460 --> 00:14:34.290
I need to be clear.

00:14:34.290 --> 00:14:37.300
Greyston was started 30 years
ago by an amazing visionary

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:40.150
entrepreneur named
Bernie Glassman, when

00:14:40.150 --> 00:14:43.130
and he started it with
the concept of a business

00:14:43.130 --> 00:14:45.040
being able to
support a community

00:14:45.040 --> 00:14:47.820
and giving back, in an
age 30 years ago when

00:14:47.820 --> 00:14:50.220
that language and a
double bottom line

00:14:50.220 --> 00:14:51.340
was not even thought of.

00:14:51.340 --> 00:14:53.870
And I encourage everyone
to look up Bernie.

00:14:53.870 --> 00:14:57.029
He has a long history as a
leader in socially engaged

00:14:57.029 --> 00:14:59.320
Buddhism, and it's a great
story, probably a little bit

00:14:59.320 --> 00:15:01.590
more than we can tell here.

00:15:01.590 --> 00:15:03.700
I joined two years
ago, and I think

00:15:03.700 --> 00:15:06.760
one of the interesting
tidbits is--

00:15:06.760 --> 00:15:08.850
it's been so long that
it's off my bio-- I used

00:15:08.850 --> 00:15:12.492
to work at a company called
Fast Search out of Norway.

00:15:12.492 --> 00:15:14.950
There may be people in this
room that are familiar with it,

00:15:14.950 --> 00:15:17.350
but it eventually grew
and was sold to Microsoft

00:15:17.350 --> 00:15:18.960
as their Mindshare business.

00:15:18.960 --> 00:15:24.670
At that point I began to look
at social entrepreneurship

00:15:24.670 --> 00:15:27.410
and the importance of it, and
the importance of our dollars

00:15:27.410 --> 00:15:31.420
going to companies that
actually share values

00:15:31.420 --> 00:15:33.290
with my own values.

00:15:33.290 --> 00:15:37.490
And I had the good fortune to
come across Greyston, which

00:15:37.490 --> 00:15:42.164
is 25 minutes north on
the MTA, and I said,

00:15:42.164 --> 00:15:44.080
this is a place I'd like
to get involved with.

00:15:44.080 --> 00:15:47.550
And I find myself
now leading it.

00:15:47.550 --> 00:15:49.870
It's been two years.

00:15:49.870 --> 00:15:52.650
At the same time, New
York state had just about

00:15:52.650 --> 00:15:56.290
passed legislation to allow
for Benefit Corporation status,

00:15:56.290 --> 00:15:59.156
and I had been exposed
to it through other types

00:15:59.156 --> 00:16:00.530
of businesses, my
other incubator

00:16:00.530 --> 00:16:03.890
that you had mentioned.

00:16:03.890 --> 00:16:05.640
It was at that
point that I said,

00:16:05.640 --> 00:16:07.440
this is an opportunity
for Greyston

00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:10.620
to take another
leadership position.

00:16:10.620 --> 00:16:13.990
We had taken a leadership
position 30 years ago.

00:16:13.990 --> 00:16:15.980
We need to take a
leadership in New York state

00:16:15.980 --> 00:16:19.570
and we need to be a voice that
says, the model must change.

00:16:19.570 --> 00:16:24.080
And there's a lot
that goes into that.

00:16:24.080 --> 00:16:26.340
Andrew hit on a
couple of the pieces,

00:16:26.340 --> 00:16:29.760
but it's the marketplace
that we're all collectively

00:16:29.760 --> 00:16:33.150
a part of, and how can I
support my fellow B Corps,

00:16:33.150 --> 00:16:36.290
how can they support me, how
can we get the message out

00:16:36.290 --> 00:16:38.580
in meetings and opportunities
like this to say,

00:16:38.580 --> 00:16:40.270
as consumers you need
to put your money

00:16:40.270 --> 00:16:42.210
and look towards--
whether it be B

00:16:42.210 --> 00:16:47.720
Corps or at least organizations
that share your values.

00:16:47.720 --> 00:16:50.290
Because if you look at the way
the economy's working today,

00:16:50.290 --> 00:16:53.540
it doesn't take you too long
to think, something's askew.

00:16:53.540 --> 00:16:57.610
And the business that accounts
for that large portion of GDP

00:16:57.610 --> 00:16:58.910
is contributing to it.

00:16:58.910 --> 00:17:03.095
And if we don't look
for ways to change it,

00:17:03.095 --> 00:17:04.720
we're going to continue
to spiral down.

00:17:04.720 --> 00:17:09.260
And I don't mean to
be overly depressing,

00:17:09.260 --> 00:17:12.290
but we really need to
think about the fact

00:17:12.290 --> 00:17:15.569
that if we were all to fly to
California and those of you

00:17:15.569 --> 00:17:21.040
watching from the Bay Area, and
got off the plane and everyone

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:24.000
there was living in
poverty, and everyone there

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:27.700
couldn't eat what they
wanted for food, that's

00:17:27.700 --> 00:17:30.440
still 12 million people
less than those people

00:17:30.440 --> 00:17:33.300
living under poverty in
our country right now,

00:17:33.300 --> 00:17:35.900
47 million people that
don't know how they're

00:17:35.900 --> 00:17:37.995
going to afford their next meal.

00:17:37.995 --> 00:17:39.370
That seems like
a problem for us.

00:17:39.370 --> 00:17:41.824
So at Greyston we're
a small bakery.

00:17:41.824 --> 00:17:43.240
To give you context,
though, we're

00:17:43.240 --> 00:17:46.580
not sitting around baking cakes.

00:17:46.580 --> 00:17:49.220
One of the great organizations
in this country is Ben

00:17:49.220 --> 00:17:49.820
and Jerry's.

00:17:49.820 --> 00:17:52.650
For 23 years we've
been providing brownies

00:17:52.650 --> 00:17:57.910
to Ben and Jerry's,
30,000 pounds a day,

00:17:57.910 --> 00:18:01.950
twelve-hour shifts of
hard work, of baking.

00:18:01.950 --> 00:18:05.780
Greyston's model
that we're known for

00:18:05.780 --> 00:18:06.977
is called open hiring.

00:18:06.977 --> 00:18:09.060
Anyone that comes to the
front door of our bakery,

00:18:09.060 --> 00:18:10.820
we give a job to.

00:18:10.820 --> 00:18:12.170
No questions asked.

00:18:12.170 --> 00:18:14.850
And there needs to be
more models like that.

00:18:14.850 --> 00:18:17.400
And that's what I hope,
through the Benefit Corporation

00:18:17.400 --> 00:18:20.080
movement, through
conversations like this,

00:18:20.080 --> 00:18:22.430
through working with Andrew
to think about employment,

00:18:22.430 --> 00:18:26.170
that a greater impact can be
made just from the community

00:18:26.170 --> 00:18:28.440
that we're in in Yonkers
to a much broader

00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:31.141
community, a global community.

00:18:31.141 --> 00:18:32.140
HOST: That's incredible.

00:18:34.710 --> 00:18:37.750
As you mentioned, you've been
doing business since 1982.

00:18:37.750 --> 00:18:40.680
How do you feel, since
Greyston's been in business,

00:18:40.680 --> 00:18:43.135
that the social enterprise
landscape has changed?

00:18:45.655 --> 00:18:47.310
MIKE BRADY: There
was none, right?

00:18:47.310 --> 00:18:48.360
30 years ago.

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:51.440
These visionaries--
there's a handful of them

00:18:51.440 --> 00:18:53.430
in their companies
that have survived,

00:18:53.430 --> 00:18:55.330
the Ben and Jerry's,
the Seventh Generations,

00:18:55.330 --> 00:18:57.740
the Greyston's-- had
an amazing vision,

00:18:57.740 --> 00:19:01.780
and they had to overcome
naysayers left and right that

00:19:01.780 --> 00:19:03.380
said, why are you
considering this?

00:19:03.380 --> 00:19:04.880
And then it still happens today.

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:06.840
I just heard a conversation
10 minutes ago,

00:19:06.840 --> 00:19:09.120
like business has
a responsibility

00:19:09.120 --> 00:19:09.960
to the environment.

00:19:09.960 --> 00:19:13.720
They have a responsibility to
the community they operate in.

00:19:13.720 --> 00:19:16.550
It needs to own up to
that responsibility.

00:19:16.550 --> 00:19:18.670
And that's what these
types of founders

00:19:18.670 --> 00:19:20.140
30 years ago are doing.

00:19:20.140 --> 00:19:22.390
Everyone in this room and
watching and the people that

00:19:22.390 --> 00:19:25.990
are interested in are now
taking note, which is great.

00:19:25.990 --> 00:19:28.900
What I hope in 30 years from
now the social enterprise term

00:19:28.900 --> 00:19:31.270
has now disappeared,
it's run its cycle,

00:19:31.270 --> 00:19:34.252
and every organization would
think back to say, what?

00:19:34.252 --> 00:19:35.710
You weren't
considering environment

00:19:35.710 --> 00:19:37.490
with the way you
ran your business?

00:19:37.490 --> 00:19:39.449
You weren't considering
your employees' welfare

00:19:39.449 --> 00:19:41.906
or the welfare of the community
when you ran your business?

00:19:41.906 --> 00:19:42.830
That just seems crazy.

00:19:42.830 --> 00:19:47.516
And that's what needs to change
in some time period soon.

00:19:47.516 --> 00:19:48.360
HOST: Definitely.

00:19:48.360 --> 00:19:49.818
Well, companies
such as yourselves,

00:19:49.818 --> 00:19:52.964
and getting into some of the
work Warby Parker is doing,

00:19:52.964 --> 00:19:55.130
are really disrupting the
way that business is done,

00:19:55.130 --> 00:19:57.610
and even the way that
consumers think about the way

00:19:57.610 --> 00:19:59.952
that business is done
and should be done.

00:19:59.952 --> 00:20:01.910
Why do you think it's
important to Warby Parker

00:20:01.910 --> 00:20:04.110
to be a Benefit Corporation?

00:20:04.110 --> 00:20:08.730
ANJALI KUMAR: So we are a
certified B Lab corporation.

00:20:08.730 --> 00:20:11.340
We're actually a C
Corp, a Delaware C Corp,

00:20:11.340 --> 00:20:13.209
and we haven't changed
our legal status.

00:20:13.209 --> 00:20:15.500
That option's only been
available since the summertime,

00:20:15.500 --> 00:20:17.550
when the legislation changed.

00:20:17.550 --> 00:20:20.820
And I think, for us, a lot of
the reason it was important

00:20:20.820 --> 00:20:23.540
was because of the community
of like-minded folks

00:20:23.540 --> 00:20:27.330
that we found within
the B Lab family.

00:20:27.330 --> 00:20:31.340
The idea that you can do
well and do good in the world

00:20:31.340 --> 00:20:34.470
is not necessarily
a new one, but it's

00:20:34.470 --> 00:20:36.680
something that was really
important for our founders

00:20:36.680 --> 00:20:38.470
to find that kind
of shared vision.

00:20:38.470 --> 00:20:41.039
And I think when they met Andrew
and the team over at B Lab,

00:20:41.039 --> 00:20:43.080
when they first started
the company, it was like,

00:20:43.080 --> 00:20:45.350
oh, they get it, this is
what we're trying to do.

00:20:45.350 --> 00:20:47.650
And we're not crazy
for having this idea

00:20:47.650 --> 00:20:50.130
that we can be this
transformative lifestyle brand

00:20:50.130 --> 00:20:52.640
offering prescription
eyewear for $95

00:20:52.640 --> 00:20:53.740
and disrupt this industry.

00:20:53.740 --> 00:20:57.150
We can do that and we can
make a lot of money doing it,

00:20:57.150 --> 00:20:58.699
hopefully, and be
really successful,

00:20:58.699 --> 00:21:00.490
but we can also have
an impact on the world

00:21:00.490 --> 00:21:01.710
in a really meaningful way.

00:21:01.710 --> 00:21:05.832
And so having that shared value
system with the folks at B Lab,

00:21:05.832 --> 00:21:07.540
and then also just
the community of folks

00:21:07.540 --> 00:21:10.570
that they bought
around this movement

00:21:10.570 --> 00:21:14.294
has been really important,
I think, to Warby.

00:21:14.294 --> 00:21:17.120
HOST: So how do you
think that technology

00:21:17.120 --> 00:21:20.100
has played a role in
Warby Parker's success,

00:21:20.100 --> 00:21:22.862
but also in just
highlighting the work

00:21:22.862 --> 00:21:25.320
that Warby Parker is doing in
giving back to the community?

00:21:25.320 --> 00:21:27.970
ANJALI KUMAR: I think it's
been absolutely critical.

00:21:27.970 --> 00:21:31.080
Without technology there would
be no Warby Parker success,

00:21:31.080 --> 00:21:33.467
frankly, because-- I
don't know if all of you

00:21:33.467 --> 00:21:35.300
are familiar with the
story of Warby Parker,

00:21:35.300 --> 00:21:38.770
but just really
briefly, the industry

00:21:38.770 --> 00:21:41.840
that we're out to disrupt
is a really longstanding,

00:21:41.840 --> 00:21:44.520
pretty entrenched
industry where there

00:21:44.520 --> 00:21:46.420
is one company,
essentially, that

00:21:46.420 --> 00:21:48.990
owns the entire ecosystem
from soup to nuts,

00:21:48.990 --> 00:21:53.330
so they own everything from
the eyewear-only brands, things

00:21:53.330 --> 00:21:57.420
like Persol or Oakley
or Oliver Peoples-- they

00:21:57.420 --> 00:21:58.720
own all of those.

00:21:58.720 --> 00:22:01.840
They have exclusive licenses
on a lot of the fashion brands

00:22:01.840 --> 00:22:04.520
that you might wear, so like
your favorite eyewear fashion

00:22:04.520 --> 00:22:09.150
brand, whether it's
Prada or DKNY or Polo.

00:22:09.150 --> 00:22:10.950
They also own the
distribution channels, so

00:22:10.950 --> 00:22:13.060
everything from a Pearle
Vision to a Sunglass Hut.

00:22:13.060 --> 00:22:17.375
They own the-- it
keeps going-- they

00:22:17.375 --> 00:22:21.980
own the in-store kind of optical
shops like Target Optical,

00:22:21.980 --> 00:22:23.530
Walmart, et cetera.

00:22:23.530 --> 00:22:26.680
And then they also own the
second-largest vision insurance

00:22:26.680 --> 00:22:28.240
plan in the States.

00:22:28.240 --> 00:22:30.510
So when you look at
that entire ecosystem

00:22:30.510 --> 00:22:34.270
and realize that's all owned
by one company, Luxottica,

00:22:34.270 --> 00:22:36.770
it's not surprising
why your glasses, which

00:22:36.770 --> 00:22:38.990
are an 800-year-old
piece of technology,

00:22:38.990 --> 00:22:40.802
cost more than
your Android phone.

00:22:40.802 --> 00:22:43.010
It starts becoming a little
clearer why that might be

00:22:43.010 --> 00:22:45.480
the case, because
these are ultimately--

00:22:45.480 --> 00:22:48.040
they're really cute, I think I
look great in these glasses--

00:22:48.040 --> 00:22:51.820
but they are ultimately
acetate and a couple-- I know,

00:22:51.820 --> 00:22:54.140
I look really good in
them, right?-- acetate,

00:22:54.140 --> 00:22:56.520
a couple metal screws,
and some glass.

00:22:56.520 --> 00:22:58.980
It's really not that
advanced technology

00:22:58.980 --> 00:23:01.110
that should be justifying
that price point.

00:23:01.110 --> 00:23:05.180
So when Warby Parker set out to
disrupt this massive industry,

00:23:05.180 --> 00:23:07.914
without access to those
distribution channels

00:23:07.914 --> 00:23:10.330
it would've been virtually
impossible to actually do that.

00:23:10.330 --> 00:23:12.666
So without technology, without
the Googles of the world,

00:23:12.666 --> 00:23:14.040
without the
Internet, there would

00:23:14.040 --> 00:23:16.680
have been no way to actually
go direct to the consumer

00:23:16.680 --> 00:23:17.340
and do that.

00:23:17.340 --> 00:23:20.430
So I think from our perspective,
social innovation really

00:23:20.430 --> 00:23:24.624
starts with that, with
creating a high-quality product

00:23:24.624 --> 00:23:26.040
of prescription
eyewear, something

00:23:26.040 --> 00:23:29.360
that people need in their
lives to actually function

00:23:29.360 --> 00:23:31.787
at a competitive price
point of what it should--

00:23:31.787 --> 00:23:33.620
it's not a low-cost
price point, it's really

00:23:33.620 --> 00:23:34.910
what glasses should cost.

00:23:34.910 --> 00:23:36.451
It's just that you've
been overpaying

00:23:36.451 --> 00:23:38.090
for them for all this time.

00:23:38.090 --> 00:23:40.507
So here's what it should
cost, and they also

00:23:40.507 --> 00:23:43.090
happen to be fashionable and all
these other wonderful things.

00:23:43.090 --> 00:23:44.560
And oh yeah, on
top of that we also

00:23:44.560 --> 00:23:47.260
give back when we sell glasses.

00:23:47.260 --> 00:23:49.860
So that's sort of our
tertiary messaging.

00:23:49.860 --> 00:23:50.915
HOST: That's great.

00:23:50.915 --> 00:23:52.040
Thank you for that context.

00:23:52.040 --> 00:23:52.790
It's so important.

00:23:52.790 --> 00:23:55.670
I don't think many of us
realize that it's basically

00:23:55.670 --> 00:23:59.212
one corporation that
manages every single aspect

00:23:59.212 --> 00:24:00.170
of the vision industry.

00:24:00.170 --> 00:24:03.930
That's amazing, down
to the insurance.

00:24:03.930 --> 00:24:09.240
So given that, that's a
lot of obstacles to face.

00:24:09.240 --> 00:24:11.022
What do you think
specifically, in terms

00:24:11.022 --> 00:24:12.730
of working with Google,
one of the things

00:24:12.730 --> 00:24:15.240
that we've been discussing
here over the last two quarters

00:24:15.240 --> 00:24:18.580
internally while promoting
B Corps at Google,

00:24:18.580 --> 00:24:22.020
is how many B Corporations
are actually using Google

00:24:22.020 --> 00:24:24.985
technology or Google apps in
order to run their business.

00:24:24.985 --> 00:24:26.610
So I'm going to start
