00:31:48.270 --> 00:31:51.470
and how rigorous that
vetting process is

00:31:51.470 --> 00:31:52.750
and the auditing process is.

00:31:52.750 --> 00:31:54.291
Maybe you can talk
to us a little bit

00:31:54.291 --> 00:31:57.890
about how you find companies
and how they find you,

00:31:57.890 --> 00:31:59.516
and what the auditing
process is like.

00:31:59.516 --> 00:32:00.307
ANDREW KASSOY: Yep.

00:32:00.307 --> 00:32:02.590
So to be clear, B Lab
is this nonprofit.

00:32:02.590 --> 00:32:05.799
We run a certification, and
the brand of the certification

00:32:05.799 --> 00:32:07.340
is called a B Corp.
It's a little bit

00:32:07.340 --> 00:32:12.900
like if you know fair trade
certification, B Corp is that,

00:32:12.900 --> 00:32:14.490
but for whole companies.

00:32:14.490 --> 00:32:18.010
And so for a company to
get certified as a B Corp,

00:32:18.010 --> 00:32:19.140
it has to do two things.

00:32:19.140 --> 00:32:21.960
One, it has to meet a minimum
set of social and environmental

00:32:21.960 --> 00:32:23.450
performance standards.

00:32:23.450 --> 00:32:27.090
So we created a
rating system, which

00:32:27.090 --> 00:32:28.810
we can get to the
technology of that,

00:32:28.810 --> 00:32:31.040
because there's a bunch of
really great opportunities

00:32:31.040 --> 00:32:31.180
there.

00:32:31.180 --> 00:32:32.763
But we basically
built a rating system

00:32:32.763 --> 00:32:35.430
that measures the impact
of a business on all

00:32:35.430 --> 00:32:37.690
of its stakeholders, not
just its shareholders,

00:32:37.690 --> 00:32:41.040
but the community, the
environment, its workers,

00:32:41.040 --> 00:32:45.600
its consumers, its supply
chain, all that kind of stuff.

00:32:45.600 --> 00:32:49.490
The second thing is that the
company makes a commitment

00:32:49.490 --> 00:32:54.120
to expand who it considers when
it makes decisions beyond just

00:32:54.120 --> 00:32:57.690
considering the value for
that particular decision

00:32:57.690 --> 00:32:59.680
on its shareholders,
but to consider

00:32:59.680 --> 00:33:02.130
all of its stakeholders
when it makes decisions.

00:33:02.130 --> 00:33:05.330
And those two things
together allow the company

00:33:05.330 --> 00:33:07.210
to get certified
as a B Corporation

00:33:07.210 --> 00:33:10.790
and join this community
of like-minded companies,

00:33:10.790 --> 00:33:14.130
and then together to speak
with collective voice.

00:33:14.130 --> 00:33:17.660
It's hard to get
certified, though.

00:33:17.660 --> 00:33:20.100
You have to do real
work, as Anjali

00:33:20.100 --> 00:33:22.060
said, to go through
that process.

00:33:22.060 --> 00:33:23.650
And part of it,
for every company,

00:33:23.650 --> 00:33:25.330
is a learning experience.

00:33:25.330 --> 00:33:28.250
As good as lots
of companies are,

00:33:28.250 --> 00:33:32.450
whether it's these two or
Patagonia or Ben and Jerry's,

00:33:32.450 --> 00:33:35.339
they all, when they go
through that process,

00:33:35.339 --> 00:33:36.880
realize there are
things that they've

00:33:36.880 --> 00:33:38.897
been focused on
that they do great,

00:33:38.897 --> 00:33:41.230
and there are lots of other
places where they fall down.

00:33:41.230 --> 00:33:43.440
And so part of that
experience of going

00:33:43.440 --> 00:33:44.830
through the
certification process

00:33:44.830 --> 00:33:47.700
is meant to also help
everybody meet them

00:33:47.700 --> 00:33:51.776
when they are, and then
help lift all boats.

00:33:51.776 --> 00:33:53.150
And one of the
interesting things

00:33:53.150 --> 00:33:54.608
that's happened as
a result of that

00:33:54.608 --> 00:33:57.460
is there are now
15,000 companies that

00:33:57.460 --> 00:34:00.300
are using that tool that
they've used to get certified

00:34:00.300 --> 00:34:03.990
as B Corps-- there are 15,000
companies who have just

00:34:03.990 --> 00:34:07.150
gone online and started to use
that tool in order to measure

00:34:07.150 --> 00:34:08.949
their own social and
environmental impact

00:34:08.949 --> 00:34:09.802
and improve it.

00:34:09.802 --> 00:34:11.760
They might not even be
ready to become B Corps.

00:34:11.760 --> 00:34:13.290
They might not be
quite good enough yet.

00:34:13.290 --> 00:34:14.880
Or they might be good
enough but just say,

00:34:14.880 --> 00:34:16.949
you know what, we don't need
to wear it on our sleeve.

00:34:16.949 --> 00:34:19.110
We really just want to use
it as an internal tool.

00:34:19.110 --> 00:34:21.080
But more and more
companies are doing that.

00:34:21.080 --> 00:34:24.370
And that's a huge
opportunity to effect,

00:34:24.370 --> 00:34:27.190
through their leadership
and their transparency,

00:34:27.190 --> 00:34:30.880
it's a huge opportunity for
them to inspire thousands

00:34:30.880 --> 00:34:33.070
and eventually hundreds
of thousands of businesses

00:34:33.070 --> 00:34:37.520
to measure and improve
their impact in the world.

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:40.850
Google could go through
that B Impact Assessment

00:34:40.850 --> 00:34:42.350
and probably learn
some great stuff.

00:34:42.350 --> 00:34:44.179
You'd probably see some
things that the company does

00:34:44.179 --> 00:34:46.137
incredibly well and find
some other things that

00:34:46.137 --> 00:34:48.730
would be a great learning
experience for the company

00:34:48.730 --> 00:34:52.650
to consider as it
continues to scale.

00:34:52.650 --> 00:34:57.890
So that's what's involved
in becoming a B Corp.

00:34:57.890 --> 00:35:00.350
One of the things I think
that's important to say

00:35:00.350 --> 00:35:04.900
is when people like
Greyston started

00:35:04.900 --> 00:35:07.660
thinking about this idea 30
years ago, of using business

00:35:07.660 --> 00:35:10.990
as a force for good, they
were like wandering around

00:35:10.990 --> 00:35:13.430
in the wilderness.

00:35:13.430 --> 00:35:16.390
There were only a few of them.

00:35:16.390 --> 00:35:18.212
And they were pretty
out there in terms

00:35:18.212 --> 00:35:19.170
of thinking about that.

00:35:19.170 --> 00:35:23.620
They were in your classic
model of disruptive technology.

00:35:23.620 --> 00:35:27.630
They were mostly
dismissed as oh, that's

00:35:27.630 --> 00:35:30.860
cute, because they
just weren't that many.

00:35:30.860 --> 00:35:36.540
And Mike's downplaying the
impact, the actual impact

00:35:36.540 --> 00:35:39.460
of what that business
has done over 30 years.

00:35:39.460 --> 00:35:41.762
Not just in Yonkers, New
York, in taking people

00:35:41.762 --> 00:35:44.220
who are coming out of prison
and turning their lives around

00:35:44.220 --> 00:35:45.990
by giving them jobs
and training them

00:35:45.990 --> 00:35:49.630
and then sending them
off to have real careers.

00:35:49.630 --> 00:35:53.120
But also the repetition of
that model by other people

00:35:53.120 --> 00:35:55.780
who've been totally inspired
by it all over the world

00:35:55.780 --> 00:35:57.510
changing the way they
think about work.

00:35:57.510 --> 00:36:01.710
Thirty years later
here we are, and there

00:36:01.710 --> 00:36:04.050
are more and more
mainstream businesses

00:36:04.050 --> 00:36:07.900
who've seen that and
recognized that they

00:36:07.900 --> 00:36:12.490
can do business and
do well while having

00:36:12.490 --> 00:36:14.810
a huge positive impact
in doing something

00:36:14.810 --> 00:36:16.120
in line with their values.

00:36:16.120 --> 00:36:18.865
And so Anjali also played down
the impact of Warby Parker

00:36:18.865 --> 00:36:25.600
is not just on their practices,
and things like a new recycling

00:36:25.600 --> 00:36:28.105
plan for glasses, or how
they treat their own workers,

00:36:28.105 --> 00:36:30.230
or how they think about
making life a hell of a lot

00:36:30.230 --> 00:36:31.910
better for consumers
than it has been

00:36:31.910 --> 00:36:35.030
by making glasses
cost $400 less.

00:36:35.030 --> 00:36:38.850
But it's also that every time
I sell a pair of glasses,

00:36:38.850 --> 00:36:40.940
an organization in
the developing world

00:36:40.940 --> 00:36:45.590
gets a pair of glasses to start
a business where they sell

00:36:45.590 --> 00:36:51.260
those glasses to people who
could otherwise never afford

00:36:51.260 --> 00:36:52.280
a pair of glasses.

00:36:52.280 --> 00:36:55.270
And so they're
changing economies

00:36:55.270 --> 00:36:58.180
throughout the developing world
through those partnerships,

00:36:58.180 --> 00:37:00.300
what they're giving away.

00:37:00.300 --> 00:37:02.470
And that's a mainstream
business that's got--

00:37:02.470 --> 00:37:05.050
I don't know how much,
but let's say $100 million

00:37:05.050 --> 00:37:08.160
of venture capital money
from venture capital funds

00:37:08.160 --> 00:37:09.890
that you've all heard of.

00:37:09.890 --> 00:37:13.860
So they're not running
a cute little thing.

00:37:13.860 --> 00:37:16.710
They're at that
next stage that's

00:37:16.710 --> 00:37:20.360
beyond people dismissing,
but people actually being

00:37:20.360 --> 00:37:23.900
threatened because they're
taking on-- through a totally

00:37:23.900 --> 00:37:26.460
mainstream, quickly
scaling business--

00:37:26.460 --> 00:37:29.620
they're taking on the accepted
order of how business is done.

00:37:29.620 --> 00:37:31.377
That's pretty threatening.

00:37:31.377 --> 00:37:33.210
And I think that there's
a-- sorry to go on,

00:37:33.210 --> 00:37:36.240
but I do think there's
a ton of power, then,

00:37:36.240 --> 00:37:39.440
in them having a
family to lean on

00:37:39.440 --> 00:37:43.220
in doing that, that
can tell those stories.

00:37:43.220 --> 00:37:46.160
And that's part of what the B
Corp community is all about.

00:37:46.160 --> 00:37:49.880
At some point, another five
or 10 or 25 years from now,

00:37:49.880 --> 00:37:51.500
that'll just be how
business is done.

00:37:51.500 --> 00:37:54.720
All businesses will be competing
to be best for the world,

00:37:54.720 --> 00:37:57.820
not just best in the world.

00:37:57.820 --> 00:38:00.700
HOST: You speak and I
have to take a moment

00:38:00.700 --> 00:38:03.140
to absorb what you said,
because it's so impactful.

00:38:03.140 --> 00:38:05.270
It's bigger, I think,
than most of us

00:38:05.270 --> 00:38:07.670
take time to really focus on.

00:38:07.670 --> 00:38:10.510
What are some ways
that you feel--

00:38:10.510 --> 00:38:13.310
we were talking a little
bit before the talk started

00:38:13.310 --> 00:38:17.870
about privilege, and how
we're not even aware of just

00:38:17.870 --> 00:38:19.482
how where we're born
or where we work

00:38:19.482 --> 00:38:20.690
gives us privilege sometimes.

00:38:20.690 --> 00:38:22.779
We just don't take the
time to think about it.

00:38:22.779 --> 00:38:24.320
Working at a place
like Google, where

00:38:24.320 --> 00:38:27.230
