00:41:41.820 --> 00:41:44.470
AUDIENCE: But I'm glad
that you brought up

00:41:44.470 --> 00:41:47.560
something like the Minimum Wage
ACT, because I wanted to ask,

00:41:47.560 --> 00:41:53.210
for B Corps, what is the stance
when it comes to dabbling

00:41:53.210 --> 00:41:58.640
in the public policy realm, and
how do you constrain yourself,

00:41:58.640 --> 00:42:01.605
or what is the most effective
model that yo've found so far?

00:42:01.605 --> 00:42:03.780
ANDREW KASSOY: Great question.

00:42:03.780 --> 00:42:06.880
So I think it's funny.

00:42:06.880 --> 00:42:11.210
Entrepreneurs run from
public policy and government

00:42:11.210 --> 00:42:13.680
as fast as they
possibly can, and so

00:42:13.680 --> 00:42:16.410
it's always this interesting
struggle of this huge community

00:42:16.410 --> 00:42:19.880
of entrepreneurs who are running
these inspiring businesses

00:42:19.880 --> 00:42:25.190
and, like it or not, businesses
affected in all kinds of ways

00:42:25.190 --> 00:42:25.935
by public policy.

00:42:25.935 --> 00:42:27.810
And so there has to be
some engagement there,

00:42:27.810 --> 00:42:30.280
and so a lot of
times they look to us

00:42:30.280 --> 00:42:33.440
to try to help play that
role, along with some other

00:42:33.440 --> 00:42:37.490
organizations that are engaged
in this sustainable business

00:42:37.490 --> 00:42:40.670
space and social
entrepreneurship.

00:42:40.670 --> 00:42:44.170
The view we've
taken is, we don't

00:42:44.170 --> 00:42:48.610
want to be a political
player, because we don't think

00:42:48.610 --> 00:42:51.550
this idea of using business
as a force for good

00:42:51.550 --> 00:42:54.740
is a left or a
right kind of idea.

00:42:54.740 --> 00:42:58.890
I mean, if you're a liberal
you can get behind the idea

00:42:58.890 --> 00:43:03.210
that we need business to
address a lot of problems

00:43:03.210 --> 00:43:07.010
that we have because business
creates a lot of externalities.

00:43:07.010 --> 00:43:08.710
If you're a free-market
conservative

00:43:08.710 --> 00:43:13.340
you can get behind the idea that
what better tool than business

00:43:13.340 --> 00:43:15.760
and free markets to solve some
of our biggest challenges?

00:43:15.760 --> 00:43:17.900
So this is not political.

00:43:17.900 --> 00:43:21.410
And so the approach we try
to take to public policy

00:43:21.410 --> 00:43:24.130
has been all about enabling.

00:43:24.130 --> 00:43:26.800
Let's do everything we can
to level the playing field,

00:43:26.800 --> 00:43:28.620
to make sure that
businesses that actually

00:43:28.620 --> 00:43:32.660
care about creating impact have
the same ability to compete.

00:43:32.660 --> 00:43:36.060
So we've gotten legislation
passed in 20 states that's

00:43:36.060 --> 00:43:40.300
actually created this corporate
form called the Benefit Corp.

00:43:40.300 --> 00:43:44.026
It's basically a legal
version of a B Corp.

00:43:44.026 --> 00:43:46.150
And the reason for doing
that was because there was

00:43:46.150 --> 00:43:48.240
a huge impediment to
businesses is being able

00:43:48.240 --> 00:43:53.320
to scale, which was
that corporate law says

00:43:53.320 --> 00:43:56.370
that a business's obligation
is to maximize value

00:43:56.370 --> 00:43:57.630
for its shareholders.

00:43:57.630 --> 00:44:01.150
Well, if that's true, then
it's really hard for a business

00:44:01.150 --> 00:44:03.400
to choose to consider
other things.

00:44:03.400 --> 00:44:06.190
It's like actual legal
liability for the directors.

00:44:06.190 --> 00:44:07.840
And so on the
public policy front,

00:44:07.840 --> 00:44:10.840
we've tried to attack issues
like that, where it's not

00:44:10.840 --> 00:44:13.680
about politics,
it's about enabling.

00:44:13.680 --> 00:44:15.430
I think there are some
great opportunities

00:44:15.430 --> 00:44:18.910
to think about how you tax
companies that are creating

00:44:18.910 --> 00:44:23.180
measurable, quantifiable
benefit for society, not just

00:44:23.180 --> 00:44:26.210
for their shareholders,
or how you tax

00:44:26.210 --> 00:44:29.210
the investment in
those businesses.

00:44:29.210 --> 00:44:33.310
It doesn't have to
be a political issue

00:44:33.310 --> 00:44:34.920
on one side of the
aisle or the other,

00:44:34.920 --> 00:44:37.520
but where we can support
these kinds of businesses

00:44:37.520 --> 00:44:41.121
and incentivize more of
them to solve big problems.

00:44:41.121 --> 00:44:42.370
HOST: That's a great question.

00:44:42.370 --> 00:44:43.132
Thank you.

00:44:43.132 --> 00:44:43.965
You have a question?

00:44:43.965 --> 00:44:46.070
AUDIENCE: I think Andy
might have touched

00:44:46.070 --> 00:44:48.410
upon what I was
going to ask anyways,

00:44:48.410 --> 00:44:52.070
but it seems like--
I was wondering

00:44:52.070 --> 00:44:54.600
if there are publicly traded
companies that are B Corps,

00:44:54.600 --> 00:44:56.600
and the reason I'm
asking is it seems

00:44:56.600 --> 00:44:59.460
there's a natural tension
between the shareholders

00:44:59.460 --> 00:45:02.900
wanting to maximize
profits, and then

00:45:02.900 --> 00:45:05.944
the company wanting to
meet the B Corp standards

00:45:05.944 --> 00:45:07.360
might have to give
up some profits

00:45:07.360 --> 00:45:10.250
to get social and
environmental changes.

00:45:10.250 --> 00:45:13.950
And we talk about impact and
getting large players to adopt,

00:45:13.950 --> 00:45:16.890
so have you sensed this tension,
and what are some of the things

00:45:16.890 --> 00:45:19.006
you're doing to bridge that gap?

00:45:19.006 --> 00:45:21.190
ANDREW KASSOY: Great question.

00:45:21.190 --> 00:45:23.780
I think Anjali can obviously
speak about this a lot,

00:45:23.780 --> 00:45:27.860
because she works at a company
that's scaling and doing really

00:45:27.860 --> 00:45:33.590
well even while keeping
all these things in mind.

00:45:33.590 --> 00:45:35.700
There's no question
there's a tension there.

00:45:35.700 --> 00:45:38.070
And that said,
there's no evidence

00:45:38.070 --> 00:45:40.730
that companies that
consider their stakeholders

00:45:40.730 --> 00:45:43.535
do worse, particularly
over the long term.

00:45:43.535 --> 00:45:45.410
And there are some
studies that show actually

00:45:45.410 --> 00:45:46.570
that they do better.

00:45:46.570 --> 00:45:48.010
And it makes sense.

00:45:48.010 --> 00:45:54.440
They retain talent better,
they avoid ridiculous risks

00:45:54.440 --> 00:45:56.930
that they shouldn't be taking,
that are irresponsible,

00:45:56.930 --> 00:45:59.300
because they're
more transparent.

00:45:59.300 --> 00:46:01.450
They are able to
create more loyalty

00:46:01.450 --> 00:46:04.670
with their consumers
and their supply chains.

00:46:04.670 --> 00:46:07.620
So they do a lot of things that
allow them to create maybe more

00:46:07.620 --> 00:46:10.819
value over the long term.

00:46:10.819 --> 00:46:12.610
So I think that's a
really important thing.

00:46:12.610 --> 00:46:14.470
That said, there's
a lot of education

00:46:14.470 --> 00:46:16.910
to do of investors, particularly
in the public markets,

00:46:16.910 --> 00:46:18.610
on that issue.

00:46:18.610 --> 00:46:21.140
And one thing just about
technology that I think

00:46:21.140 --> 00:46:22.680
is important to
say on this point.

00:46:22.680 --> 00:46:27.150
We have a ton of data, but
we're running a nonprofit,

00:46:27.150 --> 00:46:30.270
and we are certainly not--
we're not data geeks,

00:46:30.270 --> 00:46:32.660
we don't know anything
about big data.

00:46:32.660 --> 00:46:35.620
And one of the things that
we could really use help with

00:46:35.620 --> 00:46:38.010
is thinking about how
to use all of the data

00:46:38.010 --> 00:46:40.310
that we collect from
these 15,000 companies,

00:46:40.310 --> 00:46:43.500
along with data that's out
there on other companies,

00:46:43.500 --> 00:46:47.210
to start to make that case
in a much more powerful way.

00:46:47.210 --> 00:46:50.832
So if you're a big data
engineer kind of a person

00:46:50.832 --> 00:46:53.290
and wanted to spend some time
helping us try to figure that

00:46:53.290 --> 00:46:55.330
out, that's one of the
most important things

00:46:55.330 --> 00:46:56.960
if we want long
term growth here.

00:46:56.960 --> 00:46:58.626
The last thing I would
say on that front

00:46:58.626 --> 00:47:01.760
is, some company, some
public company someday

00:47:01.760 --> 00:47:05.320
is going to become a
B Corp. It'll happen.

00:47:05.320 --> 00:47:07.250
So maybe it ought to be Google.

00:47:10.491 --> 00:47:11.960
HOST: That's a
really good point.

00:47:14.850 --> 00:47:17.224
Get it in, grow the idea.

